17 2021-03-03 chest discomfort Pt reports onset of dizziness, chest tightness, shortness of breath that started acutely 45 minutes ... Read more
Close
Pt reports onset of dizziness, chest tightness, shortness of breath that started acutely 45 minutes to 1 hour after receiving her second Moderna vaccination on 2/24/21. She reported that she was told by her employer that the symptoms were due to the Moderna vaccine. She reportedly developed fever and some throat discomfort as well. Symptoms became persistent and disrupted sleep and was unable to work. She sought medical attention in the ER for persistent symptoms on 2/26/21. Extensive workup was essentially normal. She received Zofran, Decadron, IVFs, and Albuterol inhaler while in the ER. She reported improvement in her chest tightness and SOB after Albuterol. She was discharged home with instructions to f/u with her PCP in a couple of days for recheck.
17 2021-04-17 fainting Vasovagal Syncope; unauthorized age patient, 17 years of age; This spontaneous case was reported by ... Read more
Close
Vasovagal Syncope; unauthorized age patient, 17 years of age; This spontaneous case was reported by a nurse and describes the occurrence of SYNCOPE (Vasovagal Syncope) in a 17-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch no. 012A21A) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below. Concurrent medical conditions included Congenital heart disease NOS since 22-May-2003. On 01-Mar-2021 at 2:30 PM, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 01-Mar-2021 at 2:30 PM, the patient experienced SYNCOPE (Vasovagal Syncope) (seriousness criterion medically significant) and PRODUCT ADMINISTERED TO PATIENT OF INAPPROPRIATE AGE (unauthorized age patient, 17 years of age). On 01-Mar-2021, SYNCOPE (Vasovagal Syncope) had resolved. On 01-Mar-2021 at 2:30 PM, PRODUCT ADMINISTERED TO PATIENT OF INAPPROPRIATE AGE (unauthorized age patient, 17 years of age) had resolved. The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) was unknown. For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular), the reporter considered SYNCOPE (Vasovagal Syncope) to be unlikely related. No further causality assessment was provided for PRODUCT ADMINISTERED TO PATIENT OF INAPPROPRIATE AGE (unauthorized age patient, 17 years of age). No relevant concomitant medications were reported. The patient did not receive any treatment. The event, SYNCOPE (vasovagal syncope) was an acute episode and recovered quickly within minutes. Follow-up received on 06-APR-2021 included additional reporter information, date of vaccine administration, patient's race, ethnicity and other relevant medical history, start and dates of product administered and the events, anatomical location, and reporter causality. This report refers to a case of inappropriate schedule of vaccine administered for mRNA-1273 (lot #unknown) with no associated syncope reported. The reporter considered SYNCOPE to be unlikely related. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Most recent FOLLOW-UP information incorporated above includes: On 06-Apr-2021: additional reporter information, date of vaccine administration, patient's race, ethnicity and concurrent condition, additional event - Syncope, onset and stop dates of the event, - Product administered to patient of inappropriate age, injection site, and reporter causality.; Sender's Comments: This report refers to a case of inappropriate schedule of vaccine administered for mRNA-1273 (lot #unknown) with no associated syncope reported.The reporter considered SYNCOPE to be unlikely related. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

Especially in my feet I feel like they are tingling and vibrating and my calves are convulsing too. Meanwhile, my heart is fluttering and I feel like it is very hard for me to focus and I feel things crawling under my skin in my brain. The muscle convulsions are happening everywhere.

18 2021-01-14 chest discomfort I had no pain or discomfort immediately after the shot, during the 15 minute observation period, or ... Read more
Close
I had no pain or discomfort immediately after the shot, during the 15 minute observation period, or an hour after. About 2 hours later (at 2:00 pm), I developed some hives around my neck, and the part of my arm near the injection site started to become more and more sore. I applied Benadryl to the hives and they went away. However, my left arm hurt to touch or move, much worse than any vaccine I've had before (flu, HPV). That night, I had trouble sleeping because the discomfort because of the sore left arm. I also could not sleep because of chest tightness and pressure, which worsened when lying down, but that pressure did not progress to the point of wheezing (I have asthma). Sleeping on my back was the only option because sleeping on either side was painful, which worsened the chest pressure. When I woke up, my fingers felt stiff and I had joint pain in both hands, more so in my left hand. Throughout this, I did not see any redness on my arm. This day it was agonizing to move my left arm. I could pick things up, but raising it above my the height of my waist or twisting it behind my back to get on my backpack was near impossible and was avoided. The chest pressure went away. The second night, I still had trouble sleeping, but the pain was much better, although I still could not sleep on my side. When I woke up, I had no more joint pain. That day, although the left arm was still sore, I could move it pretty well. If I made too strong of a movement, it felt like the injection site would tense up, the pain would slowly ramp up, and then diminish. That afternoon, at 4:30, I was able to play tennis with minimal soreness, and that night, I was able to sleep on my side. The following day, I had a cough, but that might have been because I didn't dress for the weather, and experiences close to zero soreness.

Woke up Thursday and still felt achy but functional with a headache and nausea. Same symptoms minus the nausea on Friday.

18 2021-02-17 blood pressure increased Patient received vaccine around 430pm. As she was sitting for post-vaccine observation she told an a... Read more
Close
Patient received vaccine around 430pm. As she was sitting for post-vaccine observation she told an associate to call over Rph due to side effects. After speaking with patient she stated that her arm was numb (vaccinated arm) and that it hurt more than when she got her flu shot. I assessed both arms an her vaccinated arm was slightly swollen. I described the signs of anaphylaxis to her and told her that i would like for her to stay longer for extra monitoring and to alarm me or one of my associates if any anaphylaxis symptoms occur. Patients blood pressure was taken reading - 132/96. Patient was unsure of her baseline so i explained i will check again shortly. Patient was given water and one dose of Benadryl (25mg) at 5:25pm as well as an ice pack to place on her arm. At 6:00pm patients blood pressure was retaken (124/82) and patient stated she was well enough to go home. Her grandma was with her and stated she didn't have Benadryl at home, I recommend her to get some and gave the patient another dose (25mg) before her grandma took her home. Patient has no primary care physician.

18 2021-03-10 chest discomfort, increased heart rate, fast heart rate 18 year old female came to hospital for chest tightness, choking sensation in the throat as well as ... Read more
Close
18 year old female came to hospital for chest tightness, choking sensation in the throat as well as skin rash after receiving COVID-19 vaccine. Initially patient presented to emergency room but subsequently discharged on steroid and Benadryl. Patient had continued episode of choking as well as chest tightness and skin rash for that patient came back to emergency room. Patient had received total 5 doses of epi pen because of that. Patient was admitted to medical floor initially. Patient was given steroid, Benadryl and famotidine. Patient had 2 episodes on medical floor where she started feeling choking and chest tightness. Patient remained stable hemodynamically except for tachycardia. Patient was transferred to intensive care unit for close monitoring. D-dimer was negative, urine tox screen was negative, COVID-19 PCR was negative, EKG showed sinus tachycardia. CT scan of neck was negative. We had discussed that patient has remained stable hemodynamically in the intensive care unit and discharge planning was discussed and patient was getting ready to be discharged when she had another episode where after drinking soda patient started having that choking sensation, patient remained stable hemodynamically during this episode as well. Her symptoms had improved. She looked visibly anxious. Patient was monitored in the ICU for few more hours and patient remained stable. I checked back on her and she was able to eat her lunch. She probably had a allergic reaction to more than a vaccine but subsequent episodes are thought to be secondary to anxiety attack given situation.

Pt received vaccination at 1:30pm, pt ambulated to observation area, began feeling "dizzy and nauseous" while standing in observation area. Pt stated she continued to feel dizzy, and had tingling in her fingers. Vital signs reassessed at 1:43, BP 128/78, HR 80, unable to asses sp02 due to monitor not giving a reading. Vitals reassessed at 1:46pm, sp02 100%, HR 94. , began titrating oxygen supply down by 2l/min. Pt seemed to tolerate well for a few minutes, At 2:00pm, pt complained of tingling returning to her fingers, pt was receiving o2 4l/min, sp02 noted at 80%, increased 02 to 10l/min, called nursing lead who called 911. 2:10, unable to obtain accurate sp02. 2:17pm pt continues to receive 02 10l/min, stated she "feels okay, just weird and foggy" no tingling in hands. 2:20pm, paramedics arrive, pt states she is "a little bit dizzy" 2:35pm pt taken to hospital via stretcher with paramedics. Pt en route to hospital. At 2:00pm sp02 80%

18 2021-03-16 palpitations Approximately 7-8 minutes after receiving the vaccine, started to feel light-headed, thought she was... Read more
Close
Approximately 7-8 minutes after receiving the vaccine, started to feel light-headed, thought she was going to pass out, and her heart was racing extremely high. The health care team at the site took her blood pressure, measured heart rate, gave her water, juice and chocolate and tried to get her heart rate to drop. It was fluctuating up and down and she couldn't stand up without dizziness; we waited 45 minutes and then drove her home as she was unable to drive her own car. She was experiencing significant lightheadedness, and consistent heart racing even while lying down on the sofa/bed. This continued for several days and she stayed home from school and sports. We called her primary care doctor on the 10th and they suggested she wait another day to see how she was feeling. She started to feel a bit better by Friday, was still experiencing a bit of the tiredness, nauseous, light-headed and heart spikes, but was able to drive, move around. On Sunday evening, she started to experience increased heart rate again, lymph nodes were very painful and started experiencing the light headedness all evening. On Monday we took her to her primary care provider and they then referred her to ER for the heart racing and a EKG. The increased light headedness, feeling like she will pass out even while laying in bed, dizziness has all increased and her lymph nodes continue to be swollen and painful. It has been over a week since the vaccine and there is no clear sign of her reaction getting any better, if not worse. The EKG results indicated a new abnormality and we are trying to get her to a cardiologist. She is and had been a very healthy, varsity athlete that runs over 30 hours a week with track, and since receiving the first dose of the Moderna vaccine is unable to move very far within the house without feeling that she is going to pass out or that her heart rate is shooting up uncontrollably.

Close
I got my shot, sat down, and was reading through the information that the clinic provided me. A few minutes after, I noticed my right arm was getting warm, but I thought I was being paranoid (placebo effect). I began to feel nauseated. About another 5 minutes after feeling warm and nauseous, my ears began to ring and my vision went white. I was cold but sweating. I have passed out a handful of times before for various reasons, so I knew what was happening. I tried to signal to a volunteer from my seat that I needed help, but I ended up laying on the ground by my chair before someone came over. Once I laid down, the attention of the volunteers and nurses was on me. Three came over to assist me. They held my legs up, kept a hand on my wrist for a pulse, and fetched water. I talked myself through the dizziness and ringing in my ears. They put a cold rag on my forehead and had smelling salts on hand. Once I began to feel better, they helped me slowly sit up, and eventually helped me stand up and get into a chair. They kept a close eye on me for the next 30 minutes to make sure I didn?t have any other reactions.

Close
I received my second dose of the COVID 19 Moderna vaccine on Tuesday morning. By Tuesday night I started to have virtually every side effect that Moderna listed including; fatigue, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, chills, nausea and vomiting, and extreme fever. The next morning as I woke up in attempt tp get ready for work, I was not feeling any better and began to feel light headed, and felt the need to vomit. As I had the feeling of needing to vomit, I turned to do so and fainted. From accounts by my family, I was told I woke up, and quickly passed out a second time. As I was awoken, there was probably a minute before I fainted for a third time. All three times I was told I lost consciousness. I was awoken and by that point my family had contacted emergency responders. Paramedics arrived and took all necessary vitals. I did not pass out after that third time. As I expected all side effects Moderna listed, I did not expect to feel as bad as I did and I thought it was worth reporting what happened to be the next day. It caused a panic and I was scared and nervous as I was unsure why that was happening. I've tried to look up articles and links between passing out and the vaccine and all I can find is people fainting as they get the vaccine (which is common for any shot) but nothing for fainting that long after the vaccine was administered. I just wanted to report my incident.

After receiving my second dose, I started to develop mouth ulcers covering the entire inside of my mouth. Throughout the weekend, they continued to develop. I went to the ER to receive pain medication, as the ulcers were so bad that I could not talk or eat. The following morning, I passed out going to pick up my medication at CVS, where I was taken back to the hospital in an ambulance and had a 103 degree fever. I was given IV fluids and was sent on my way. I was on strict bedrest for 4 days, until on Thursday 04/22/2021, I was readmitted to the ER due to worsening of the sores and lack of nutrition. For 3 days since then, I have been on IV fluids, pain medication, and taking a steroid solution to help the ulcers in my mouth lessen. The doctors here believe that it is an extremely strong reaction to the COVID-19 vaccine second dose.

04/26/2021 got the shot. An hour later, I had shortness of breath. Kept persisting throughout the week and worsened. On sunday, 05/02/2021 between the hours of 12AM to 2AM, my shortness of breath got worse to the point where I could not breathe. In general, I felt my back and chest tighten. I could only breathe (faintly) to survive. If I took any deeper breaths, my back and chest would hurt even more. As time progressed, My right neck got stiff. Then right my jaw got stiff. Then the right side of my head got stiff. Eventually, the whole right side of my body was numb -- I could move it still but it was still numb and stiff. This happened simultaneously with the breathing issues. This entire time, my whole was tensing, it felt like I could feel my veins while it rushed blood. It was terrible. I thought I was going to die. I did not know which breath would be my last, because every breath got worse and worse. I went to sleep around 2AM and I would periodically wake up. When I'd wake, the pain still persisted. It never went away. Eventually I got up to go to work around 8AM, the right side of my body wasn't as numb and the breathing wasn't as bad, but you could still tell there was an issue. This issue persisted throughout the day. As of now, these issues are not as persistent, but at least once a day, I still feel the effect. It sucks. A nurse called me (working at the urgent care I gave information about) , on 05/03/2021 saying if I was going to see a primary doctor. I told her that I have an appointment with one on 05/10/2021. She said that though they called me on 05/02/2021 towards the end of the day and told me everything was fine, that they looked a little deeper and realized that the shape of my cells were weird and that when I go to my primary doctor, they'd be able to access my information. This is of a complete shock because the shape of my cells were never weird before. This happened as a result of the covid-19 vaccine. This is reaction must be put into the VAERS system.

Close
Passing out; Window of blurry vision before passing out for about 30 seconds; Upon regaining consciousness, patient immediately vomited; Fever; Feeling achy; Chills; Tired; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of LOSS OF CONSCIOUSNESS (Passing out) in a 19-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch nos. 031L20A and 044B2V) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below. No medical history reported. Concomitant products included ETHINYLESTRADIOL, FERROUS FUMARATE, NORETHISTERONE ACETATE (LO LOESTRIN FE) for Birth control. On 20-Mar-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 17-Apr-2021, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. After a week all symptoms went away.

Rapid eye movement like "having a mini-seizure"; Fainted; Feeling warm; A spontaneous report (United States) was received from a pharmacist concerning a 21-year-old, female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and fainted and experienced to have rapid eye movement like "having a mini-seizure" and feeling of warmth. The patient's medical history included historical seizures. Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter. On 02 Feb 2021, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number:026L20A) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 02 Feb 2021, a few minutes after the injection, the patient fainted then recovered but again fainted and was noted to have rapid eye movement like "having a mini-seizure". HCP managed her with ice pack as patient complained of feeling warm and she recovered in less than 30 minutes. Treatment information was not provided. The outcome for events fainted, rapid eye movement like "having a mini-seizure"" and feeling warm were resolved.; Reporter's Comments: This spontaneous report concerns a 21-year-old, female patient with historical seizures. who received experienced the patient fainted then recovered but again fainted and was noted to have rapid eye movement like "having a mini-seizure." The event occurred a few minutes after the administration of mRNA-1273 vaccine (Batch number: 026L20A, expiration date: unknown). Treatment administered include Icepack and outcome is resolved. Based on the information provided which includes a strong temporal onset between the vaccine administration and the event, a causal association cannot be excluded. However, event is confounded by the subject's history of seizures. Feeling warm is consistent with the safety profile of the product.

21 2021-03-15 inflammation of the heart muscle, chest pain, fibrin d dimer increased Patient received first dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 2/10/21 and had a large, red, inflamed ar... Read more
Close
Patient received first dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 2/10/21 and had a large, red, inflamed area on her arm at the injection site for a few days, but otherwise tolerated vaccine well. She received the second dose of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 3/10/21 and the next day (3/11/21) developed fatigue and lightheadedness while exercising, which continued for the next few days. She developed acute onset, sharp chest pain on 3/13/21 AM which did not resolve so she presented to an ED. Vitals were normal but labs notable for troponin I which peaked at 4.36, CK 758, d-dimer 640. CBC/CMP and EKG were unremarkable and initial TTE with EF ~45%. Repeat TTE obtained a few days later with normal LV and RV size/function without any wall motion abnormalities. Cardiac MRI obtained with normal LV function (EF 64%) but late gadolinium enhancement in a subepicardial distribution within the inferolateral wall of the left ventricle at the base most compatible with myocarditis. ESR and CRP were normal. Further workup to determine etiology of myocarditis was negative (ANA, ANCA, RF, hepatitis panel, HIV, full respiratory viral panel, COVID-19 PCR). She was placed on metoprolol succinate 12.5mg XL daily and will follow up with a cardiologist as an outpatient. Family concerned that COVID-19 vaccine was the trigger/underlying etiology of her myocarditis.

21 2021-03-20 loss of consciousness Minutes after receiving the first dose of the Moderna vaccine, patient complained of difficulty brea... Read more
Close
Minutes after receiving the first dose of the Moderna vaccine, patient complained of difficulty breathing. I asked if she was wheezing and she said no. A doctor in the clinic came over and even though it wasn't time for patient and her sister to leave (based on 15-minutes after receiving the vaccine) he initially suggested that they might be fine to go, but after patient told him of her symptoms and at my urging he decided to have her stay a little longer. I think it was at this time that he had someone check her pulse. I don't know what the pulse reading was. He stepped away and shortly afterwards patient started complaining that her throat felt strange and was making it hard to breathe. The doctor immediately came back over, found patient was having difficulty breathing and holding herself upright in the chair. I held her by the shoulders to keep her from falling while the doctor also steadied her and asked a worker in the room for an epi-pen. The worker didn't seem to react much to the request so he told her louder that he needed an epi-pen. She started searching her area and the doctor started yelling across the room to others that he needed an epi-pen. It seemed like others initially took the demand less urgently than they should, but eventually someone came with an epi-pen. By this time I don't think patient was very conscious, if at all. Sometime during this time the doctor also instructed someone to call 911. The doctor tried using the epi-pen but at first he had some kind of cap on it that prevented it from working. He removed the cap and not finding an easy way to have a sterilized injection site he injected the epi-pen through patient's jeans. Soon afterwards a cot was brought out and workers had me step aside as they took patient and put her on the cot. Patient seemed to gradually become more aware of her surroundings and it wasn't long before she appeared to me to be fully conscious once again. They checked her blood pressure and pulse and maybe did other tests during this time. Eventually the ambulance arrived and patient was very clear with everyone that she did not want to incur the expenses of riding in the ambulance and I offered to bring her wherever they suggested that she should go. They watched and evaluated her for a while and eventually had her sign the form declining the ambulance transportation. They suggested that she make an appointment with her doctor but did not suggest that we take patient to an emergency room. We departed and patient did not afterward seem to experience any symptoms from the vaccine other than some of the general feelings of being sick, soreness at the injection site, etc. that others report with the Moderna vaccine.

21 2021-04-09 loss of consciousness Immediately after receiving the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine the patient began to feel nauseous, hot and... Read more
Close
Immediately after receiving the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine the patient began to feel nauseous, hot and her arm was hurting. I kept her in the immunization booth and monitored her. Within a minute of her initial feeling she stated that she was having trouble seeing and was "going to black out". She immediately lost consciousness, her eyes rolled back, and her head went limp and fell back. She then began a twitching movement, made a snorting noise and then all of her limbs went rigid and extended straight out. At the first sign of her reaction we paged management and then as soon as she had loss of consciousness we contacted 911. She regained consciousness and was able to start answering my questions within 30 seconds to 1 minute. We did get the patient water and began to fan her to help cool her off. She was able to tell me who she was, where she was and why she was here. We also gave her some chips and had her eat slowly and drink small sips. She had stated that she was very nervous at the beginning of our pre immunization questions. She told us after that she had not eaten a lot before coming for the shot, but did eat more than normal because she knew she was coming in. She contacted her parents to inform them of the situation. She was able to recount everything prior to her loss of consciousness. When EMS arrived she was able to answer their questions. They took her vitals and all were in normal range, BP=119/66, pulse=98. They asked her to stand and she was able to stand and maintain balance on her own, but stated her legs felt a little "shaky". She refused transport to the hospital by EMS, but did call her roommate to come pick her up. I had her wait in the COVID waiting area until her roommate arrived. I called her around 4pm (same day) to check on her and she said she is feeling much better. Her mom (a nurse) also came down to stay with her and was with her when I called.

I developed Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura (low levels of platelets) and menorrhagia due to the vaccine according to my doctor. I believe there have been about 30 cases of this occurring so far. In my case, I took the vaccine and felt relatively tired for two days. There were no other symptoms. About a week later, I got my period after not having it for a couple months. The blooding was light for a few days, but then got extremely heavy. After about a week of very heavy bleeding, I went to urgent care. They took blood tests, and found that I had a critically low level of platelets (6 platelets when the normal range is 150-400). I was admitted to the ER for multiple days, and they gave a platelet transfusion and IVIG fluids, which has helped considerably. I also had to take steroids to suppress my immune system so that my platelets could increase.

The patient's medical history was not provided. Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter. On 06 Jan 2021, the patient received her first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 intramuscularly in her right deltoid for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 06 Jan 2021, the patient experienced a sore arm, fever, chills, itching and burning. On 07 Jan 2021, on the site where the patient received the injection, she felt numbness and weak. Her whole right-side body would jerk uncontrollably. The patient went to two emergency rooms where they stated they did not know what was wrong and gave her a steroid injection that temporarily helped calm her down. On 08 Jan 2021, the patient stared at the door and everything went blank. She could not talk and when she tried to talk, she felt like she had the hiccups. She experienced her whole chest hurting when she had a hiccup. On 25 Jan 2021 and 26 Jan 2021, the patient saw two neurologists, who did testing. The patient's jerking was random, there were no triggers for it, and she did not know how to control or stop it. These adverse reactions made the patient become aggravated very quickly, which was not like her. On an unknown date, the patient stated it was the first day in the past month she had been able to talk all day. Treatment for the events included a steroid shot. Action taken with the second dose of mRNA-1273 in response to the event was not reported. The outcome for the events, sore arm/ burning, fever, chills, itching, numbness, weak, whole right side would jerk uncontrollably, everything went blank, couldn't talk and when she tried to talk she felt like she had the hiccups and her whole chest hurt, and quickly became aggravated, was not reported.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information which indicates a strong temporal association between the use of the product and the onset of the reported events a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Chills, fever, injection site pruritus and injection site pain are consistent with the known safety profile of mRNA-1273.

Severe anaphylaxis allergic reaction; Passed out on the ground; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer concerning a 22-year-old female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and passed out on the ground and had a severe anaphylaxis allergic reaction. The patient's medical history was not provided. Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter. On an unknown date, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their second of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 intramuscularly for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. About 10 minutes after receiving the second dose of the Moderna vaccine, the patient passed out on the ground having a severe anaphylaxis allergic reaction. Treatment for the event included two doses of epinephrine IM in addition to diphenhydramine, ondansetron, and steroids to prevent a rebound reaction. 911 was called and after epinephrine and diphenhydramine were administered, the patient was immediately transported to the hospital where she stayed for 6 more hours for observation, fluids, and further medications. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not applicable. The events, passed out on the ground and severe anaphylaxis allergic reaction, were considered resolved; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Anaphylactic reaction is a listed event in CCDS.

She was seated in the recliner She reported to have itchy watery eyes, chest tightness. Patient's boyfriend noted her tongue and eyelids to appear slightly swollen compared to baseline. Patient denied dizziness, chest pain, shortness of breath, body rash or itching. Patient maintained normal speech and normal unlabored respirations. BP was checked and noted to be normal. O2 sat 99%. Patient received benadryl 50mg PO. Patient's O2 saturation and HR fluctuated, BP remained stable throughout. EMS arrived. A right AC IV was placed, Solumedrol 125mg IVP was administered by EMS. Patient was transferred onto EMS stretcher, still requiring nonrebreather. Patient was escorted to ED for further management of anaphylxis post Moderna vaccine.

- 22 year-old female - Tested positive for COVID-19 on January 31, 2021. My symptoms lasted 21 days and started with major gastrointestinal issues, headache, and cough. - Had a negative COVID-19 PCR test on February 25, 2021 - this negative PCR was needed to travel back. - Landed on February 28, 2021 and completed my quarantine at my parents house. - I returned to work on the 15th of March, 2021. - Over the weekend I traveled and flew back on April 5, 2021. Because I had flown, I was doing a courtesy and went to the local store to get a rapid antigen test. APRIL 8, 2021 - left work at 12:30 and went to the store to get the rapid antigen test which came back positive. I was told by the nurses that it only came back positive because it has been less than 90 days since I initially tested positive. I was told I did not need to self-isolate and could go about as normal. I had my second dose of the Moderna vaccine on this day at 2:00 p.m. I went to get my second jab. Just to be safe, after my jab I went to the local urgent care where they took a nasal swab for a PCR test. The results of the PCR test came back Saturday, April 10 about 7:30 that evening and the result was "NOT DETECTED". SYMPTOMS: Thursday, April 8th about 8:00 pm I started to have difficulty breathing and taking a deep breath was difficult. I put it down to anxiety about the initial positive test. Saturday, the difficulty breathing continued, along with new pressure in my chest. I was unable to sleep Saturday night - as soon as I was nearly sleep, I would wake up gasping for a breath. Sunday, the pressure in my chest continued and so did the difficulty breathing. I went to the Emergency Room on Sunday, April 11 about 4:15 pm - they took a chest x-ray, ran blood tests, and did an EKG which all came back completely normal - no pneumonia, heart attack, or blood clots. The doctor gave me a 1 mg dose of an anti-anxiety medicine because he could tell I was very stressed. He later prescribed me Prednisone (3 tablets a day for 4 days). As of today, I am still having a very hard time taking a full, deep breath and continue to have pressure in my chest.

Fainted; Vomiting; Nausea; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of SYNCOPE (Fainted) in a 22-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch no. 036B21A) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below. The patient's past medical history included No adverse event (No Reported Medical event). On 07-Apr-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 09-Apr-2021, the patient experienced SYNCOPE (Fainted) (seriousness criterion medically significant), VOMITING (Vomiting) and NAUSEA (Nausea). At the time of the report, SYNCOPE (Fainted), VOMITING (Vomiting) and NAUSEA (Nausea) outcome was unknown. The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) was unknown. Treatment information was not provided.; Sender's Comments: This case concerns a 22-year-old female with a serious unexpected event of syncope and nonserious expected nausea and vomiting. Event onset 3 days after first dose mRNA-1273. Event outcomes unknown. Based on current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

Chest hurting; Breathing becomes painful; Tingling sensation on her tongue and says that it feels bigger than normal; Tingling sensation on her tongue and says that it feels bigger than normal; Feeling cold; A spontaneous report was received from a healthcare professional concerning a 23-year-old female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced chest hurting, breathing became painful, tingling tongue, tongue discomfort, feeling cold. The patient's medical history was not provided. No concomitant medications were provided. On 09 Jan 2021, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot Number: 012L20A) for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 09 Jan 2021, the patient experienced a tingling sensation on her tongue and felt that it was bigger than normal. She was given Diphenhydramine as an intervention. The patient started to feel cold. After 20 minutes, breathing became painful and her chest was hurting. The patient was given epinephrine and was transported to the hospital for continued monitoring. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported. The outcome of the events, chest hurting, breathing became painful, tingling tongue, tongue discomfort, feeling cold, was considered were not recovered/resolved.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 23-year-old female patient who received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot 012L20A), and who experienced the serious unlisted events of Chest pain and Painful respiration and the non-serious unlisted events of tingling tongue, tongue discomfort, and feeling cold. Patient was treated with Benadryl and EpiPen prior to being transferred to hospital. Based on the current available information and temporal association between vaccination and the onset of events on the day of vaccination, a causal relationship cannot be excluded and the events are considered possibly related to the vaccine.

Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported. The outcome of the event, syncope, was unknown. The events, weakness and twitching of the face, were considered not resolved.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 23-year-old, female, who experienced serious unexpected event of syncope, and non-serious unexpected events of asthenia and muscle twitching. The events of syncope, asthenia occurred 2 days after mRNA-1273 (Lot# 025J20-2A), while the event of muscle twitching occurred on an unspecified date after mRNA-1273 (Lot# 025J20-2A). Treatment details were not provided. Based on temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. 23 2021-05-11 cerebrovascular accident Central Venous Sinus Thrombosis in Superior Sagittal Sinus I arrived home at 12:38 on Sunday, 5/9, ... Read more
Close
Central Venous Sinus Thrombosis in Superior Sagittal Sinus I arrived home at 12:38 on Sunday, 5/9, and opened the door to see my sister with facial droop, slurred speech and a contracted right hand/fingers. She was crying and immediately knew she was having a stroke. She had been trying to clasp some jewelry while getting ready for Mother's Day. She was able to walk down to the car with me no problem (no extremity involvement other than right hand/fingers). We arrived at the hospital within 10 minutes and she was a Code Stroke. A CT scan showed the clots as well as a tiny Subarachnoid bleed and she was admitted to NeuroICU. The symptoms waxed and waned for a few hours and at one point she developed the droop again, had headache and heartburn and vomited. A CT scan was repeated after some Heparin had entered her system and it was stable/not worse; subarach bleed was not changed and Heparin was continued. She has now been admitted for 3 days and the Heparin is complete. She is now being transitioned to oral Xaralto. She has no deficits whatsoever and has made a full recovery so far. We are still pending the results of her coagulation studies to see if she has a hereditary condition. The doctors believe the clot is due to her Nuvaring Estrogen, which is most likely. However, I would still like to report this event just in case.

Obese female patient with history of diabetes and seizure came to our pharmacy for second Moderna covid dose. A few minutes after receiving the vaccine, she was feeling lightheaded and nausea. I asked the patient to come back in to the consultation room where she could sit or lay down on the floor. The patient was able to walk back into the room with a little assistance from her mother. It also appeared that she went into a seizure, her upper body stiffened up and her arms were slightly flailing. I immediately called 911 and about 1 minute later, both the mother and I could clearly see the patient breathing as indicative by the rising/lowering chest. I also felt a stronger pulse on her wrist. I did not inject the epi pen. Paramedics arrived shortly and after about 5-10 minutes of talking to her, the patient began to gain conscious but looked exhausted. They transported her to the hospital. Per the mother, patient was completely fine after the first dose of Moderna; also just had a seizure a few days before the second Moderna dose. The whole incident was about 20 minutes from administering the vaccine to paramedics transporting her away.

24 2021-02-05 heart rate irregular, heart rate increased, chest discomfort, loss of consciousness On January 21 I received my first dose of Moderna vaccine on my left arm. After the vaccine I had a ... Read more
Close
On January 21 I received my first dose of Moderna vaccine on my left arm. After the vaccine I had a red lump that was hot and a bruise that only lasted 2 days. Everything was fine until the January 28th when I developed a large red lump during the day while at work that was severely itchy and hot. When I got home from work I had a low grade fever. I made an appointment with my primary care for the next day which was Friday the 29th. My doctor told me she believes I had cellulitis. I was given an antibiotic 2x a day for 7 days. She drew a purple circle around the area and told me that if it goes outside the marked area or I feel any new symptoms, to go to the emergency room. Saturday morning on the 30th i woke up to my entire arm red and hot. I felt like I had a huge sunburn. I couldn?t put my sweatshirt on because it was so hot. The emergency room doctor told me I was fine and to keep taking the antibiotics that were given to me yesterday from my primary care doctor. After the emergency room I went to work and started to feel dizzy and nauseous. My hands became sweaty but the rest of my body was cold. I started having a butterfly feeling in my chest. My Apple Watch alerted me that my heart rate was over 100 bpm. That night before bed I had another low grade fever. On Sunday the 31st I noticed the red area was gone but instead it was a dark purple. I felt okay Sunday besides a rapid pulse. Monday February 1st I woke up out of a dead sleep sweating, butterfly feeling in my chest and dizzy. I tried to take my pulse while laying down but it was so fast I couldn?t keep up with it. I put my Apple Watch on which alerted me immediately that my pulse was 152 bpm. I slowly got up but then I passed out falling off of my bed. I couldn?t get any words out because my heart was beating so fast that I couldn?t breathe. I was sweating horribly and had a hard time walking. Had absolutely no strength in my left hand, my arm was purple/red, cold and numb. My arm felt like someone punched me repeatedly and gave me a dead arm. I called my primary doctors office and they were able to get me in that afternoon. All morning my pulse was spiking and then drastically dropping. About an hour and a half before I went to the doctor everything was fine. I was able to talk but still struggled with breathing while talking. The doctor ordered an EKG which came back clear. My pulse and blood pressure was also fine. The doctor told me she believed all of the symptoms I had were from the medication I take at night (doxazosin-to relax my muscles and help with sleep.) She also told me she believed some of it was my mental health issues taking over. She told me the cellulitis looked fine and sent me home. Later that day I felt exhausted and when I woke up from a nap, I had a fever of 100.5. Took Tylenol and it dropped to 99.5 but wouldn?t go any lower. February 2nd I woke up to a large red ring outside of the purple marker, numb finger tips and butterfly feeling in my chest. All day I received alerts that my pulse was falling and spiking. I sent my primary doctor an email and she told me she didn?t think it was cellulitis anymore, maybe a hematoma but she wasn?t sure. Since January 28th I still struggle everyday with the butterfly feeling in my chest, blurry vision, low grade temps, alerts of pulse, dizziness and breathing difficulties. My arm is always hot, my finger tips are numb and sometimes the strength in my hand is gone. The top of my arm is always a dark purple with red blotches and other times my entire arm is red and hot. When my pulse is very fast, I have a hard time talking, remembering what I was going to say and focusing. I?ve had multiple coworkers ask me if I?m okay because I?ll randomly stop talking and stare off and then I?m alerted that my pulse has either spiked or dropped drastically after spiking. My pulse is never consistent. It is always ranging from 57-155bpm. I realized at first I may have what they call ?COVID arm? but my symptoms haven?t gotten any better. No answers have been given to me or a diagnosis. The first diagnosis that they thought was cellulitis. Then it was ?in my head and behavioral.? Then it was a hematoma. Now it?s an ?I don?t know.? I have tried Benadryl for the itching, ice packs for the days that I?m swollen, Tylenol for the fevers and pain but I never have any relief.

The patient recovered well, laughing at herself and apologizing because she's never had this happen to her before. I assured her that no apology was necessary, I'm glad she's feeling better, and that she should stay as long as she needs. After about 15 more minutes the patient rose from her chair said that she felt fine and was going to leave to go get breakfast. I wished her well and allowed her to leave.

Tachycardia (140 bmp), not relieved with rest. Chest pain/tightness. Arm turned purple and all the vasculature was present in the right arm and chest. Admitted to hospital, ultrasound revealed the subclavian vein was completely occluded down to the basilic vein near the elbow. CT scan showed pulmonary emboli in both lungs. Was placed on heparin drip and released from hospital on 04/4/21. Started on 10 mg Eliquis BID for one week on 4/4, now on 5 mg Eliquis BID for 6 months. 05/19/21: Received diagnosis of Factor V Leiden heterozygous mutation. Arm pain/swelling remains periodically.

ON 3 JUNE 2021 @ 1453, "25-year-old female who presents to the emergency department with 2 days of worsening left-sided chest pain associated with some myalgias shortness of breath she received her second covid vaccination on the first of June. she also has some bilateral anterior shin pain soreness into her arms as well. Denied any fever and a productive cough any nausea or diarrhea". Patient was admitted to ICU on 3 June for NSTEMI in setting of chest pain/SOB with elevated TnT. Significant elevation of TnT >3K with unremarkable ECG. TIMI score 1, grace 52. Given her age etiology concerning for possible Myocarditis but will start appropriate tx for NSTEMI and order formal TTE.....Patient has been diagnosed with Myopericarditis. The patient didn't have any significant changes on her EKG, however, she did have elevated troponins up to 3134 ng/L which trended down to 2455 ng/L on recheck. Given the pleuritic nature of her chest discomfort, MD suspected Acute Myopericarditis. She is still symptomatic and thus, MD recommended she take high-dose NSAIDs. MD would not too keen on starting her on steroids and/or colchicine unless she doesn't get better on follow up evaluation. Echocardiogram showed intact ejection fraction. MD have sent off additional labs to look for other causes of myopericarditis. The patient should also be on a low-dose of beta blocker and ACE inhibitor. She'll follow with her primary care provider and cardiology.

At 1:15pm, vitals are: blood pressure: 160/100, heart rate:81 and unable to get oxygen saturation due to long acrylic nails. Client reports not taking any medications, no known allergies and only has history of rosacea. PHN alert Lead PHN to come assist with client who is having a reaction. PHN assesses client and observes flushed face and rash on upper back and front neck area. Client reports to that she feels "lightheaded", PHN asks RN to get gravity chair and switch client to gravity chair. Client able to transfer herself to anti-gravity chair by herself. PHN offered client Benadryl and client accepted. Client reports she can get family to pick her up. At 1:18pm, PHN provides client with oral Benadryl 50 mg. Vitals are heart rate: 81 and blood pressure: 170/100. Client reports she feels "hot", her head "feels weird" and she feels like her "heart is racing." RN assists by fanning client. RN takes over vitals blood pressure: 180/130 at 1:20pm and client reports feeling hot everywhere. While PHN is assessing client PHN activates 911 at 1:23pm. At 1:25pm, client reports she feels "throbbing in her head and chest", "heavy breathing", "lightheaded" and PHN notes flushed face. Vitals are: Blood pressure:180/120 heart rate:86 and oxygen: 98%. Fire department arrives at 1:29pm and assumes care. At 1:34pm client was wheeled out of facility on gurney and was taken to hospital.
